{{also|Deadman|dead man}}
==English==

===Etymology===
From {{compound|en|dead|man}}. In the sense referring to a safety switch, the notion of an operator who is dead is the [[figurative]] archetype representing any incapacitation, absence, or inattention. See also {{m|en|Dead Hand}} in that regard.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|deadmen}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[corpse]]
#: {{ux|en|There is no '''deadman''' to be found at Deadman's Curve.}}
# {{lb|en|construction}} A long object, often a [[timber]] or [[log]], buried to serve as an anchor for a wall or for [[stays]].
#: {{ux|en|The building code requires '''deadmen''' for retaining walls.}}
# {{lb|en|rail transport|manufacturing|agriculture|safety equipment}} A [[cutout]] device that operates in the event that an operator releases the control handles, leaves the operator's seat, or otherwise seems to be no longer present and alert.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1962|month=April|title=Beyond the Channel: Western Germany: The Henschel 4,000 h.p. V320 diesel|journal=Modern Railways|page=274|text=[...] a Brown-Boveri '''deadman''''s control; [...].}}

